<div id="review_6145134" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/6145134" />
    <a title="Kristen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/330755-kristen"><img alt="Kristen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1189018106p2/330755.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/6145134?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kristen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kristen" href="/user/show/330755-kristen">Kristen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Those interested in understanding how immigrants feel when moving to the States from their homeland</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer6145134" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12194022857411958409">Any amazing portrayal about a family from the Dominican Republic moving to New York. One great part about this book is that it isn&apos;t from only one person&apos;s perspective. It details the POV of daughters and parents, because they each had a different experience. Some wanted to quickly become as American as possible, some wanted to hold strongly to their Dominican roots. I love the way it is told via vignettes (great for my short attention span!). But my favorite aspect is how the story is told back</span>
  <span id="freeText12194022857411958409" style="display:none">Any amazing portrayal about a family from the Dominican Republic moving to New York. One great part about this book is that it isn't from only one person's perspective. It details the POV of daughters and parents, because they each had a different experience. Some wanted to quickly become as American as possible, some wanted to hold strongly to their Dominican roots. I love the way it is told via vignettes (great for my short attention span!). But my favorite aspect is how the story is told backwards, so that once you reach the end (and sometimes even the next chapter), you better understand one of the preceding stories. Some people might like to know this information up front, to understand a character's life chronologically. But you know what? That is not how life is. When we as natives meet immigrants, we form prejudices and opinions about them...because we know nothing about them, only what we want to believe. Only once we start getting to know them and their past do we understand them and what prompted them to come to our great country. And this is the experience the reader encounters in this book. I know it only received average ratings on this website, but I think it is amazing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12194022857411958409" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


