    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1246658074" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1246658074" />
    <a title="Sadia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29157851-sadia"><img alt="Sadia" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1246658074?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sadia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sadia" href="/user/show/29157851-sadia">Sadia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1246658074" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14491001898420311618"> Rarely do high school students enjoy the books they are assigned to read by their English teachers. However Julia Alvarez’s novel, How the Garcia Girls Lost their Accents, proves that among the tiresome texts, there are also some texts that are refreshing. How the Garcia Girls Lost their Accents, describes the hard transition immigrants must make in order to feel at home in a new country. Garcia sisters, Carla, Sandra, Yolanda, and Sofia move to the United States after their father gets into tr</span>
  <span id="freeText14491001898420311618" style="display:none"> Rarely do high school students enjoy the books they are assigned to read by their English teachers. However Julia Alvarez’s novel, How the Garcia Girls Lost their Accents, proves that among the tiresome texts, there are also some texts that are refreshing. How the Garcia Girls Lost their Accents, describes the hard transition immigrants must make in order to feel at home in a new country. Garcia sisters, Carla, Sandra, Yolanda, and Sofia move to the United States after their father gets into trouble with the Dominican Republic's secret police. They must leave their luxurious lives in exchange for a middle class life in New York City. Alvarez writes the story of four sisters who have a hard time finding themselves in a new environment. Having read, How the Garcia Girls Lost their Accents, I feel students should read this novel on their own. Although students can read it as a whole class, I feel students should read it independently. Reading it individually, would mean a different experience to each reader. Each reader can judge it for themselves and can choose for themselves what they get from it.<br /><br /> I, especially liked how Julia Alvarez portrayed the idea of family in her novel. Although at times, the reader may be slightly confused by the characters’ actions, you can sense a strong relationship between everyone in the Garcia family. Adjusting to a new country and their cultures can be very complicated and hard but Alvarez thoroughly explains how the Garcia girls always had family with them (physically and spiritually). Carla, the oldest Garcia sister had a difficult time adjusting to American culture. She, like many immigrants grasped onto the idea of family to find comfort in the transition: “the seemingly endless list of familiar names would coax her back to sleep with a feeling of safety, of a world still peopled by those who loved her.” Carla acknowledges the differences between her and Americans. She didn't feel like she belonged because of her connections to Dominican culture. However her family continues to stand by her and she feels protected and loved by their presence. Julia Alvarez writes a realistic story about family through the four Garcia girls. Although the Garcia family are immigrants and face problems due to their status, readers can feel a connection to the characters’ loving family. They act as any other family. They help each other during tough times and get through such events together. Readers can’t help but be reminded of their families when they read this novel. Alvarez portrays the idea of family beautifully as the Garcia family experience the best and worst times of their lives. <br /> Julia Alvarez also describes how time only strengthens the connection between family. The Garcia family experienced many hardships after moving to America and readers understand this to be true “even after they'd been married and had their own families and often couldn't make it for other occasions, the four daughters always came home for their father's birthday.” The Garcia family made time for each other and it shows greatly when they come back together. Although the girls are adults, they all desire to see each other again. The Garcia family show how meaningful family is. High school students should read Julia Alvarez’s novel, How the Garcia Girls Lost their Accents, on their own time. Readers can interpret the book for themselves because no two readers feel the same way after reading a book. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14491001898420311618" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


