  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_87072844" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/87072844" />
    <a title="Aaron Alexius" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3209505-aaron-alexius"><img alt="Aaron Alexius" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1377406285p2/3209505.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/87072844?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aaron Alexius" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aaron Alexius" href="/user/show/3209505-aaron-alexius">Aaron Alexius</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3209505-aaron-alexius?shelf=annotated-bibliography">annotated-bibliography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3209505-aaron-alexius?shelf=novels-and-novellas">novels-and-novellas</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3209505-aaron-alexius?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer87072844" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13887099137284327316"><b>Snapshot:</b>The four Garcia daughters come of age and into wisdom while negotiating the transition from being Dominican nobles to being America immigrants visiting the island. Each section looks at an age in the life of the protagonists, beginning with their young adult lives revisiting family on the island. Successive chapters go back in time 5-10 years each time, eventually detailing how each of the Garcia girls became deeply complex Garcia women.<br/><br/><br/><b>Hook:</b> This is a collection of first person narrati</span>
  <span id="freeText13887099137284327316" style="display:none"><b>Snapshot:</b>The four Garcia daughters come of age and into wisdom while negotiating the transition from being Dominican nobles to being America immigrants visiting the island. Each section looks at an age in the life of the protagonists, beginning with their young adult lives revisiting family on the island. Successive chapters go back in time 5-10 years each time, eventually detailing how each of the Garcia girls became deeply complex Garcia women.<br /><br /><br /><b>Hook:</b> This is a collection of first person narratives told from the point of view of various sisters. It reminds me of sitting with my brothers and sister, telling the stories of our growing lives: each sister weaves a tale of some critical event in the way that she saw it. This definitely falls into a "Immigration Story" text as well as a "Coming of Age (one of the few that I've read that have women as the main character)" and has some elements of "Historic Fiction." <br /><br /><br /><b>Challenges:</b> The method of section organization, while intriguing, must be introduced through a pre-read in order to fully appreciate the style. I found that scanning the section titles was enough for me. Some Spanish that goes untranslated.<br /><br />Another challenge is in deciphering the narrator. Each story is told from a different perspective, but this frame of reference is never announced and must be inferred. <br /><br /><br /><b>Student in mind:</b> While I have a knee jerk reaction to recommend this to my Central and South American students (I would still recommend it to them), I actually thought about some, seemingly, very different people: Ebla and Amino who came to this country from Somalia, and Joyce whose parents moved to New York from China. Joyce has mentioned getting burned out on teachers constantly recommending Chinese Immigration stories, but I wondered if she would find it interesting to read an immigration story from a different culture. This led me to Ebla and Amino who are trying to make a seat for themselves as women in a country where the role of women is very different from their home country (this change of women's role is reflected in the Garcia's change from D.R. to the U.S.). Perhaps Ebla and Amino could get a lot out of the text by comparing and contrasting their own stories. <br /><br /><br /><b>Conference Notes:</b> Point of View is changes quite frequently in this story, from whose point of view is the story being told in the chapter you're reading right now? How can you tell? As the book develops, the reasons for Papi Garcia's fear of men in uniform becomes more and more clear, what events in the story lead to that fear? How does it effect his life in the States? Cultural views of Religion and Sex vary greatly in the U.S. as compared to the D. R., how would you describe that difference? What events from the text show these different attitudes? How do the Garcia daughters feel about religion and sex? Their parents? <br /><br /><br /><b>Level:</b> Reading level is medium-easy, students might be able to complete the book at 6th grade. However, this text has a maturity difficulty: students younger than 14 may not be able to understand and relate to the text as I assume it was intended. Thus 10-12 grade independent reading. Good for developing reading endurance without an overload of Tier III words.<br /><br /><br /><b>Other:</b> Coming to America. Person vs. Society. Being a women in misogynistic society. Old vs. New world ideas.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13887099137284327316" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


